Mitchell:

I have found building reading speed in QS has been a bit of a problem as 
well.  I don&#39;t ascribe it to any flaw in the alphabet, however.  I have 
not tried to learn another alphabet, such as Greek or Cyrillic, as an 
adult so it is difficult to judge whether the problem could be connected 
to the fact that most of us are introduced to our language&#39;s writing 
system when quite young and, possibly, a child&#39;s mind is more malleable 
than an adult&#39;s, as is evidenced by children&#39;s alleged ease in learning 
language.  

But I believe it more likely that the heart of the problem lies in the 
limited amount of practice we get in reading QS.  From our birth we are 
surrounded by the ubiquity of the roman alphabet.  It is everywhere, and 
we see it constantly.  Our facility in reading it is so great that we 
read and comprehend the meaning even when we have no desire to, such as 
advertising on the side of a bus. QS is not ubiquitous.  Most of us 
using it primarily see our own QS rather than other people&#39;s.  If the 
people on this list communicated in QS, at least part of the time, I 
believe we would see an improvement in our ability to read QS.

We write one symbol at a time so it is easy to spell by sound in QS as 
we go.  However, we read in larger chunks, words at the minimum, or 
several words in a glance, if we are to read with any speed.  Obviously, 
the connection in the brain between the symbol and the sound must be one 
hundred percent solid so that no conscious thought is required. 
 Apparently, this takes lots of practice -- considerably more than most 
of us have given QS.  Think of the years you have spent reading TO 
before you conclude that QS is in some way deficient.

I am more proficient at reading QS now than I was in the past since I 
have spent more time at it recently, but it is still not as automatic as 
reading the traditional orthography (TO).  I almost feel as if I have to 
shift gears when I read it. But I am finding that I read whole words and 
more now than I used to since I started writing more in it.  I write 
notes in QS in my files and sometimes intersperse it with TO.  I have 
mentioned to my secretary that she should learn to read it, but she 
hasn&#39;t found the time yet.  My law partner (my father) has expressed 
some annoyment at my use of QS, which he expresses by noting &quot;if you get 
hit by a truck, I won&#39;t be able to read these notes in your files.&quot;  I 
will have to convince my secretary to learn QS.  After all, they all 
used to learn shorthand and didn&#39;t complain.  Once she can read it, she 
can transliterate it for my father if the proverbial truck with my name 
on it appears.



Paige Gabhart



